Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: State Bank of Mauritius, Total Kenya

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-07-01T15:42:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-01/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-state-bank-of-mauritius-total-kenya.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index advanced for a second day, adding 0.7 percent to 1,188.91
by the 3 p.m. close in Accra, the highest close since May 18.  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  climbed for a sixth
day, rising 0.6 percent to 854.94 at the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek, the longest winning streak since March 25. Kenya’s
All-Share Index snapped four days of gains, retreating 0.2
percent to 70.37 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined 1.1 percent to 24,696.83
by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index snapped two
days of gains, slipping less than 0.1 percent to 2,097.10 by the
1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  State Bank of Mauritius Ltd. (SBM)  , the country’s
second-largest lender by market value, advanced 0.5 rupees, or
0.5 percent, percent, to 96.50 rupees, the highest since April
22, on speculation the company will increase its dividend
payout.  “Investors are anticipating an improved dividend for its
financial year through June,” Kishen Nadassen, a senior
research analyst at Cim Stockbrokers Ltd., said in a phone
interview. “The lender pays a single dividend each year,
announced by mid-July. We expect it to rise to 2.90 rupees a
share from 2.75 rupees last year.”  Total Kenya Ltd. (TKNL)  , the Kenyan unit of  Total SA (FP) ,
dropped 50 cents, or 2.1 percent, to 23 shillings, the lowest
since Dec. 31, 2002. Oil in  New York  fell as much as 2.1 percent
on signs of slowing manufacturing growth in  China .  To contact the reporter on this story:
